cs.LG, cs.DM, cs.AI, cs.SI, cs.IT

The paper discusses the problem of learning a maximum likelihood Markov network, which is a common topic in machine learning and statistics. The use of tree-width as a measure of complexity suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) sub-category. However, the use of global, integer-programming based, approximation algorithms suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. The discussion of computational hardness and approximation further supports the possibility of cs.DM and cs.LG. The use of Markov networks and the analysis of their properties suggest that the paper may also belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-categories. Finally, the use of optimization techniques suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category.
